Carson Jay Robison ((1890-08-04)August 4, 1890 – (1957-03-24)March 24, 1957) was an American country music singer and songwriter.
In 1924, he moved to New York City and was signed to his first recording contract with the Victor Talking Machine Company.

In one of their first collaborations, Robison accompanied Dalhart on the landmark recording of "Wreck of the Old '97" b/w "The Prisoner's Song" (1924), widely regarded as country music's first million-seller.
In 1928, after Dalhart made a personnel change without consulting Robison, their relationship ended.
From 1928 to 1931 he teamed with Frank Luther, recording songs for various labels and appearing on WOR radio in New York City.
In 1932, he started his own band, Carson Robison's Pioneers (later renamed The Buckaroos), and continued touring and recording through the 1930s and 1940s.
It was during this period that Robison made some of the earliest tours of a country musician in the Britain, appearing there in 1932, 1936, and 1938.
According to Billboard, his 1942 reworking of the standard "Turkey in the Straw", with new lyrics relating to World War II, was that year's most popular song.
His most famous recording was 1948's "Life Gets Tee-Jus Don't It", a worldwide hit for MGM Records.
Also, in 1956, he wrote and recorded the novelty rock and roll song, "Rockin' and Rollin' With Grandmaw."
Robison died in 1957 in Poughkeepsie, New York.

The son of a champion fiddler, he became a professional musician in the American Midwest at the age of 15, primarily as a whistler working with Wendell Hall, "The Red-Headed Music Maker", on the early 1920s music hall circuit.
Although his impact is generally forgotten today, he played a major role in promoting country music in its early years through numerous recordings and radio appearances.
Also that year, Robison started a professional collaboration with Vernon Dalhart, one of the era's most notable singers.

Although the break up did not prove lucrative for either artist, Robison continued to record for decades to come.

In the late 1940s and early 1950s, he appeared on the Grand Ole Opry.
